### Unit 3a: Basic Objects (structs), Assignment of Objects, . and -> Operators, Use of getline(), Checking an Input Stream for Failure, Using C++ string class

#### Basic Objects (structs)
A struct in C++ is a collection of variables under one name. It's similar to a class, but it does not have member functions.

```cpp
struct Point {
    int x, y;
};

int main() {
    Point p1, p2;
    p1.x = 1; p1.y = 2;
    p2 = p1; // Assigns p1 to p2
    return 0;
}
```

#### Assignment of Objects
Objects can be assigned to each other using the `=` operator.

```cpp
Point p1, p2;
p1.x = 1; p1.y = 2;
p2 = p1; // p2 now has the same values as p1
```

#### . and -> Operators
The `.` operator is used to access members of an object, and the `->` operator is used when accessing members of a pointer to an object.

```cpp
Point p;
p.x = 1; p.y = 2;

Point *pp = &p;
pp->x = 3; // Same as p.x = 3
```

#### Use of getline()
The `getline()` function is used to read a line from an input stream, such as `std::cin`.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string line;
    std::getline(std::cin, line); // Reads a line from cin
    return 0;
}
```

#### Checking an Input Stream for Failure
The input stream `std::cin` has a member function `fail()` to check for failure.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::cin >> n;
    if (std::cin.fail()) {
        std::cin.clear(); // Clears the error flags
        std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n'); // Ignores the rest of the input
    }
    return 0;
}
```

#### Using C++ string class
The `std::string` class provides a convenient way to work with strings in C++.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string s1 = "Hello";
    std::string s2 = "World";
    s1 += s2; // Concatenates s2 to s1
    return 0;
}
```

### Unit 3b: Defining Your Own Classes, public vs. private, Constructors and Destructors and when they execute, Defining Member Functions, Splitting your class into files

#### Defining Your Own Classes
A class in C++ is a user-defined type that can contain member variables and member functions.

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    int a;
    void func() { /* ... */ }
};
```

#### public vs. private
The `public` keyword allows members to be accessed from outside the class, while the `private` keyword restricts access to within the class.

```cpp
class MyClass {
private:
    int a;
public:
    void func() { /* ... */ }
};
```

#### Constructors and Destructors and when they execute
A constructor is a special member function that is called when an object is created. A destructor is a special member function that is called when an object is destroyed.

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass() { /* Constructor */ }
    ~MyClass() { /* Destructor */ }
};
```

#### Defining Member Functions
Member functions are defined inside the class definition.

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    void func() { /* ... */ }
};
```

#### Splitting your class into files
You can split the definition of a class into multiple files by placing the class definition in a header file and the implementation in a source file.

```cpp
// MyClass.h
class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass();
    ~MyClass();
    void func();
};

// MyClass.cpp
#include "MyClass.h"

MyClass::MyClass() {
    /* Constructor implementation */
}

MyClass::~MyClass() {
    /* Destructor implementation */
}

void MyClass::func() {
    /* Function implementation */
}
```

### Unit 4a: Linked Lists, Implementing basic operations (push, pop to front, middle, or back), Efficiency of various operations given variations of their implementation (with or without tail pointer, etc), Pros and cons compared to arrays

#### Linked Lists
A linked list is a data structure that stores a sequence of elements, where each element points to the next element in the sequence.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

void push(Node** head, int data) {
    Node* newNode = new Node;
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = *head;
    *head = newNode;
}

void pop(Node** head) {
    if (*head == nullptr) return;
    Node* temp = *head;
    *head = (*head)->next;
    delete temp;
}
```

#### Efficiency of various operations
The efficiency of operations in a linked list depends on the implementation. For example, adding an element to the front is efficient, but adding an element to the middle or back is less efficient.

#### Pros and cons compared to arrays
Linked lists have dynamic size and can be resized, but they have slower access times than arrays.

### Unit 4b: vector<T> and deque<T> basic operation, Efficiency of their operations

#### vector<T> and deque<T> basic operation
The `std::vector` and `std::deque` classes provide efficient ways to store and manipulate sequences of elements.

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> v;
    v.push_back(1);
    v.push_back(2);
    v.pop_back();

    std::deque<int> d;
    d.push_front(1);
    d.push_back(2);
    d.pop_front();
    d.pop_back();
    return 0;
}
```

#### Efficiency of their operations
The efficiency of operations in `std::vector` and `std::deque` depends on the operation. For example, adding an element to the front of a `std::deque` is efficient, but adding an element to the middle or back of a `std::vector` is less efficient.

### Unit 4c: Doubly linked lists, deque<T> class, Implementing basic operations, Efficiency of various operations given variations of their implementation (with or without tail pointer, etc)

#### Doubly linked lists
A doubly linked list is a data structure that stores a sequence of elements, where each element points to the previous and next elements in the sequence.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* prev;
    Node* next;
};

void push(Node** head, int data) {
    Node* newNode = new Node;
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = *head;
    newNode->prev = nullptr;
    if (*head != nullptr) {
        (*head)->prev = newNode;
    }
    *head = newNode;
}

void pop(Node** head) {
    if (*head == nullptr) return;
    Node* temp = *head;
    *head = (*head)->next;
    if (*head != nullptr) {
        (*head)->prev = nullptr;
    }
    delete temp;
}
```

#### Efficiency of various operations
The efficiency of operations in a doubly linked list depends on the implementation. For example, adding an element to the front or back is efficient, but adding an element to the middle is less efficient.

#### deque<T> class
The `std::deque` class provides efficient ways to store and manipulate sequences of elements, similar to a doubly linked list.

### Unit 4d: Multidimensional arrays, Memory layout of a multidimensional arrays, Passing multidimensional arrays to functions

#### Multidimensional arrays
A multidimensional array is an array of arrays. The memory layout of a multidimensional array depends on the order of elements.

```cpp
int arr[2][3] = {
    {1, 2, 3},
    {4, 5, 6}
};
```

#### Memory layout of a multidimensional arrays
The memory layout of a multidimensional array is row-major order, meaning the elements are stored in row order.

#### Passing multidimensional arrays to functions
You can pass a multidimensional array to a function by passing a pointer to the first element.

```cpp
void func(int arr[][3]) {
    // Access elements of the array
}
```

### Unit 4e: syntax and use, advantages of passing by reference, const references

#### syntax and use
You can pass a variable by reference using the `&` operator.

```cpp
void func(int& x) {
    // Access the variable by reference
}
```

#### advantages of passing by reference
Passing by reference allows you to modify the original variable within the function.

#### const references
You can pass a variable by const reference using the `const` keyword.

```cpp
void func(const int& x) {
    // Cannot modify the variable
}
```

### Unit 4f: Checking for failure when opening a file, Using C++ ifstream and ofstream classes for File I/O, Checking for failure when attempting to receive input (extract a value from the stream)

#### Checking for failure when opening a file
You can check for failure when opening a file using the `fail()` member function of the `std::ifstream` class.

```cpp
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt");
    if (file.fail()) {
        // Handle error
    }
    return 0;
}
```

#### Using C++ ifstream and ofstream classes for File I/O
The `std::ifstream` class is used to read from a file, and the `std::ofstream` class is used to write to a file.

```cpp
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt");
    std::ofstream file("example.txt");
    return 0;
}
```

#### Checking for failure when attempting to receive input
You can check for failure when attempting to receive input from a file using the `fail()` member function of the input stream.

```cpp
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt");
    int n;
    if (file >> n) {
        // Successfully read input
    } else {
        // Handle error
    }
    return 0;
}
```

